o compute, more generally, fundamental groups of spaces that are glued together from other spaces. For example, the 2-sphere formula_167 can be obtained by gluing two copies of slightly overlapping half-spheres along a neighborhood of the equator. In this case the theorem yields formula_168 is trivial, since the two half-spheres are contractible and therefore have trivial fundamental group. The fundamental groups of surfaces, as mentioned above, can also be computed using this theorem.\nIn the parlance of category theory, the theorem can be concisely stated by saying that the fundamental group functor takes pushouts (in the category of topological spaces) along inclusions to pushouts (in the category of groups).\nCoverings.\nGiven a topological space formula_169, a continuous map \nformula_170\nis called a \"covering\" or formula_171 is called a \"covering space\" of formula_169 if every point formula_80 in formula_169 admits an open neighborhood formula_175 such that there is a homeomorphism between the preimage of formula_175 and a disjoint union of copies of formula_175 (indexed by some set formula_178),\nformula_179\nin such a way that formula_180 is the standard projection map formula_181\nUniversal covering.\nA covering is called a universal covering if formula_171 is, in addition to the preceding condition, simply connected. It is universal in the sense that all other coverings can be constructed by suitably identifying points in formula_171. Knowing a universal covering \nformula_184 \nof a topological space formula_1 is helpful in understanding its fundamental group in several ways: first, formula_2 identifies with the group of deck transformations, i.e., the group of homeomorphisms formula_187 that commute with the map to formula_1, i.e., formula_189\nAnother relation to the fundamental group is that formula_190 can be identified with the fiber formula_191 For example, the map\nformula_192\n(or, equivalently, formula_193) is a universal covering. The deck transformations are the maps formula_194 for formula_195 This is in line with the identification formula_196 in particular this proves the above claim formula_197\nAny path connected, locally path connected and locally simply connected topological space formula_1 admits a universal covering. An abstract construction proceeds analogously to the fundamental group by taking pairs formula_199, where formula_200 is a point in formula_1 and formula_26 is a homotopy class of paths from formula_4 to formula_200. The passage from a topological space to its universal covering can be used in understanding the geometry of formula_1. For example, the uniformization theorem shows that any simply connected Riemann surface is (isomorphic to) either formula_206 formula_207 or the upper half-plane. General Riemann surfaces then arise as quotients of group actions on these three surfaces.\nThe quotient of a free action of a discrete group formula_94 on a simply connected space formula_85 has fundamental group \nformula_210\nAs an example, the real formula_72-dimensional real projective space formula_212 is obtained as the quotient of the formula_72-dimensional unit sphere formula_214 by the antipodal action of the group formula_215 sending formula_216 to formula_217 As formula_214 is simply connected for formula_219, it is a universal cover of formula_212 in these cases, which implies formula_221 for formula_219.\nLie groups.\nLet formula_94 be a connected, simply connected compact Lie group, for example, the special unitary group formula_224, and let formula_225 be a finite subgroup of formula_94. Then the homogeneous space formula_227 has fundamental group formula_225, which acts by right multiplication on the universal covering space formula_94. Among the many variants of this construction, one of the most important is given by locally symmetric spaces formula_230, where\nIn this case the fundamental group is formula_225 and the universal covering space formula_237 is actually cont