, in direct analogy with the definition of formula_269\nIf formula_171 happens to be path-connected and simply connected, this sequence reduces to an isomorphism\nformula_271\nwhich generalizes the above fact about the universal covering (which amounts to the case where the fiber formula_272 is also discrete). If instead formula_272 happens to be connected and simply connected, it reduces to an isomorphism\nformula_274\nWhat is more, the sequence can be continued at the left with the higher homotopy groups formula_275 of the three spaces, which gives some access to computing such groups in the same vein.\nClassical Lie groups.\nSuch fiber sequences can be used to inductively compute fundamental groups of compact classical Lie groups such as the special unitary group formula_276 with formula_277 This group acts transitively on the unit sphere formula_278 inside formula_279 The stabilizer of a point in the sphere is isomorphic to formula_280 It then can be shown that this yields a fiber sequence\nformula_281 \nSince formula_282 the sphere formula_278 has dimension at least 3, which implies \nformula_284\nThe long exact sequence then shows an isomorphism\nformula_285\nSince formula_286 is a single point, so that formula_287 is trivial, this shows that formula_288 is simply connected for all formula_289\nThe fundamental group of noncompact Lie groups can be reduced to the compact case, since such a group is homotopic to its maximal compact subgroup. These methods give the following results:\nA second method of computing fundamental groups applies to all connected compact Lie groups and uses the machinery of the maximal torus and the associated root system. Specifically, let formula_96 be a maximal torus in a connected compact Lie group formula_291 and let formula_292 be the Lie algebra of formula_293 The exponential map\nformula_294\nis a fibration and therefore its kernel formula_295 identifies with formula_296 The map\nformula_297\ncan be shown to be surjective with kernel given by the set formula_178 of integer linear combination of coroots. This leads to the computation \nformula_299 \nThis method shows, for example, that any connected compact Lie group for which the associated root system is of type formula_300 is simply connected. Thus, there is (up to isomorphism) only one connected compact Lie group having Lie algebra of type formula_300; this group is simply connected and has trivial center.\nEdge-path group of a simplicial complex.\nWhen the topological space is homeomorphic to a simplicial complex, its fundamental group can be described explicitly in terms of generators and relations.\nIf formula_1 is a connected simplicial complex, an \"edge-path\" in formula_1 is defined to be a chain of vertices connected by edges in formula_1. Two edge-paths are said to be \"edge-equivalent\" if one can be obtained from the other by successively switching between an edge and the two opposite edges of a triangle in formula_1. If formula_306 is a fixed vertex in formula_1, an \"edge-loop\" at formula_306 is an edge-path starting and ending at formula_306. The edge-path group formula_310 is defined to be the set of edge-equivalence classes of edge-loops at formula_306, with product and inverse defined by concatenation and reversal of edge-loops.\nThe edge-path group is naturally isomorphic to formula_312, the fundamental group of the geometric realisation formula_313 of formula_1. Since it depends only on the 2-skeleton formula_315 of formula_1 (that is, the vertices, edges, and triangles of formula_1), the groups formula_312 and formula_319 are isomorphic.\nThe edge-path group can be described explicitly in terms of generators and relations. If formula_96 is a maximal spanning tree in the 1-skeleton of formula_1, then 'formula_310 is canonically isomorphic to the group with generators (the oriented edge-paths of formula_1 not occurring in formula_96) and relations (the edge-equivalences corresponding to triangles in formula_1). A similar result holds if formula_96 is replaced by any simply connected\u2014in particular contractible\u2014subcomplex of formula_1. This often gives a practical way of computing fundamental groups and can be used to show that every finitely presented group arises as the fundamental group of a finite simplicial complex. It is also one of the classical methods used for topological surfaces, which are classified by their fundamental groups.\nThe \"universal covering space\" of a finite connected simplicial complex formula_1 can also be described directly as a simplicial complex using edge-paths. Its vertices are pairs formula_329 where formula_330 is a vertex of formula_1 and \u03b3 is an edge-equivalence class of paths from formula_306 to formula_330. The formula_334-simplices containing formula_329 correspond naturally to the formula_334-simplices containing formula_330. Each new vertex formula_338 of the formula_334-simplex gives an edge formula_340 and hence, by concatenation, a new path formula_341 from formula_306 to formula_338. The points formula_329 and formula_345 are the vertices of the \"transported\" simplex in the universal covering space. The edge-path group acts naturally by concatenation, preserving the simplicial structure, and the quotient space is just formula_1.\nIt is well known that this method can also be used to compute the fundamental group of an arbitrary topological space. This was doubtless known to Eduard \u010cech and Jean Leray and explicitly appeared as a remark in a paper by Andr\u00e9 Weil; various other authors such as Lorenzo Calabi, Wu Wen-ts\u00fcn, and Nodar Berikashvili have also published proofs. In the simplest case of a compact space formula_1 with a finite open covering in which all non-empty finite intersections of open sets in the covering are contractible, the fundamental group can be identified with the edge-path group of the simplicial complex corresponding to the nerve of the covering.\nRelated concepts.\nHigher homotopy groups.\nRoughly speaking, the fundamental group detects the 1-dimensional hole structure of a space, but not higher-dimensional holes such as for the 2-sphere. Such \"higher-dimensional holes\" can be detected using the higher homotopy groups formula_348, which are defined to consist of homotopy classes of (basepoint-preserving) maps from formula_214 to formula_1. For example, the Hurewicz theorem implies that for all formula_351 the formula_72-th homotopy group of the \"n\"-sphere is\nformula_353 \nAs was mentioned in the above computation of formula_354 of classical Lie groups, higher homotopy groups can be relevant even for computing fundamental groups.\nLoop space.\nThe set of based loops (as is, i.e. not taken up to homotopy) in a pointed space formula_1, endowed with the compact open topology, is known as the loop space, denoted formula_356 The fundamental group of formula_1 is in bijection with the set of path components of its loop space:\nformula_358\nFundamental groupoid.\nThe \"fundamental groupoid\" is a variant of the fundamental group that is useful in situations where the choice of a base point formula_133 is undesirable. It is defined by first considering the category of paths in formula_360 i.e., continuous functions\nformula_361,\nwhere formula_82 is an arbitrary non-negative real number. Since the length formula_82 is variable in this approach, such paths can be concatenated as is (i.e., not up to homotopy) and therefore yield a category. Two such paths formula_364 with the same endpoints and length formula_82, resp. formula_82' are considered equivalent if there exist real numbers formula_367 such that formula_368 and formula_369 are homotopic relative to their end points, where formula_370\nThe category of paths up to this equivalence relation is denoted formula_371 Each morphism in formula_372 is an isomorphism, with inverse given by the same path traversed in the opposite direction. Such a category is called a groupoid. It reproduces the fundamental group since\nformula_373.\nMore generally, one can consider the fundamental groupoid on a set formula_374 of base points, chosen according to the geometry of the situation; for example, in the case of the circle, which can be represented as the union of two connected open sets whose intersection has two components, one can choose one base point in each component. The van Kampen theorem admits a version for fundamental groupoids which gives, for example, another way to compute the fundamental group(oid) of formula_375\nLocal systems.\nGenerally speaking, representations may serve to exhibit features of a group by its actions on other mathematical objects, often vector spaces. Representations of the fundamental group have a very geometric significance: any \"local system\" (i.e., a sheaf formula_376 on formula_1 with the property that locally in a sufficiently small neighborhood formula_175 of any point on formula_1, the restriction of formula_272 is a constant sheaf of the form formula_381) gives rise to the so-called monodromy representation, a representation of the fundamental group on an formula_72-dimensional formula_383-vector space. Conversely, any such representation on a path-connected space formula_1 arises in this manner. This equivalence of categories between representations of formula_2 and local systems is used, for example, in the study of differential equations, such as the Knizhnik\u2013Zamolodchikov equations.\n\u00c9tale fundamental group.\nIn algebraic geometry, the so-called \u00e9tale fundamental group is used as a replacement for the fundamental group. Since the Zariski topology on an algebraic variety or scheme formula_1 is much coarser than, say, the topology of open subsets in formula_64 it is no longer meaningful to consider continuous maps from an interval to formula_1. Instead, the approach developed by Grothendieck consists in constructing formula_389 by considering all finite \u00e9tale covers of formula_1. These serve as an algebro-geometric analogue of coverings with finite fibers.\nThis yields a theory applicable in situations where no great generality classical topological intuition whatsoever is available, for example for varieties defined over a finite field. Also, the \u00e9tale fundamental group of a field is its (absolute) Galois group. On the other hand, for smooth varieties formula_1 over the complex numbers, the \u00e9tale fundamental group retains much of the information inherent in the classical fundamental group: the former is the profinite completion of the latter.\nFundamental group of algebraic groups.\nThe fundamental group of a root system is defined in analogy to the computation for Lie groups. This allows to define and use the fundamental group of a semisimple linear algebraic group formula_94, which is a useful basic tool in the classification of linear algebraic groups.\nFundamental group of simplicial sets.\nThe homotopy relation between 1-simplices of a simplicial set formula_1 is an equivalence relation if formula_1 is a Kan complex but not necessarily so in general. Thus, formula_354 of a Kan complex can be defined as the set of homotopy classes of 1-simplices. The fundamental group of an arbitrary simplicial set formula_1 are defined to be the homotopy group of its topological realization, formula_397 i.e., the topological space obtained by gluing topological simplices as prescribed by the simplicial set structure of formula_1.\nNotes.\n&lt;templatestyles src=\"Reflist/styles.css\" /&gt;"}
